🧠 OS Concept 1: User Threads vs Kernel Threads (Deep Trap)

We saw basics earlier; now interview nuance.

Core Difference
User Threads

Managed by user library.

OS may not even know each thread.

Kernel Threads

Managed directly by OS.

OS schedules them.

🔥 Trap Question

Q: Why can one blocked user thread block all user threads?

Because kernel sees one process only.

If process blocks:

👉 all user threads block.

🧠 Analogy

User threads:

Friends coordinating internally.

Kernel sees whole group as one.

🎯 Placement Question

Which supports true parallelism?

👉 Kernel threads.

🧠 Memory Trick
User threads = hidden from OS
Kernel threads = visible to OS
🧠 OS Concept 2: Reentrant Code

🔥 Product companies may ask.

1️⃣ Simple Idea

Reentrant code can be safely used by multiple threads at same time.

Why Safe?

Because it doesn’t rely on shared mutable data.

Example Idea

Uses:

✔ local variables

Avoids:

❌ global shared state

🧠 Analogy

Shared pen (unsafe)

vs

Everyone has own pen (safe)

🔗 Connection

Important in:

signal handlers
thread-safe libraries
🎯 Placement Question

Q: What makes code reentrant?

👉 No unsafe shared state.

🧠 Memory Trick
Reentrant = safe re-entry
⚙️ COA Concept 3: Write Allocate vs No Write Allocate

Another cache trap.

Write Miss happens:

Data not in cache.

What now?

Write Allocate

Bring block into cache first, then write.

✔ good with write-back

No Write Allocate

Write directly to memory.

Don’t load into cache.

✔ sometimes better for one-time writes

🎯 Trap Question

Often paired with:

Write Back ↔ Write Allocate
Write Through ↔ No Write Allocate (common pairing)
🧠 Memory Trick
Allocate = bring to cache
No allocate = skip cache
⚙️ COA Concept 4: Direct Mapped vs Set Associative (Deep Dive)
Direct Mapped

Each memory block has exactly one cache place.

Simple.

Fast lookup.

But conflicts possible.

Set Associative

Block maps to a set, then can go to multiple lines inside set.

Less conflict.

Used widely.

🧠 Analogy

Direct mapped:

Student fixed one locker only.

Set associative:

Student can use any locker in assigned row.

🎯 Placement Question

Q: Why set associative preferred?

👉 Reduces conflict misses.

🧠 Memory Trick
Direct = rigid
Set = flexible
